<article>
    <h1>Miss</h1>
    <h2></h2>
    <section>
        <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/textview" title="The Straits Times">The Straits Times</a>
        - <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/20201206/textview" title="The Straits Times - 2020-12-06"><time>2020-12-06</time></a>
        - <span>LIFE | FOOD &amp; DRINK</span>
        - <span role="byline"></span>
    </section>

    <p>The restau­rant’s open front lets in plenty of sun­light dur­ing lunch, en­sur­ing good snap­shots of the food.</p>
    <p>But it also lets in the heat, es­pe­cially on a blis­ter­ing day. It is worse if you are seated out­doors, though things get more com­fort­able in the even­ing.</p>
    <p>AM­BI­ENCE</p>
    <p>The weather aside, the restau­rant ex­udes a lazy mood in the day that is helped by pots of plants in­side and out. Ceil­ing lamps de­signed to look like fish­ing ap­pa­ra­tus add that ex­tra bit of re­sort at­mos­phere.</p>
    <p>Small ta­bles can be joined to­gether for groups of five, while sin­gle or cou­ple din­ers can sit at the counter to watch the chefs at work.</p>
    <p>In the even­ing, the at­mos­phere changes as the dim light­ing and a more gen­er­ous flow of al­co­hol en­cour­age a more buzzy mood.</p>
    <p>THE BOT­TOM LINE: The place is chill and the food is good.</p>


